      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Does Durable's built-in CRM matter?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes, for small businesses. Durable is the only builder with built-in CRM. Contact form submissions go into a lead pipeline. Automatic follow-up reminders. Email drip campaigns. Invoice generation. The plumber doesn't need a separate CRM‚ÄîDurable handles it. 10Web and Webflow have forms only‚Äîsubmissions go to email."
        }
      }
    ]
  }} />

  <!-- BRUTALIST HERO - Coupon site style -->
  <section class="relative overflow-hidden bg-gradient-to-br from-orange-50 via-amber-50 to-red-50">
    <!-- Diagonal line pattern -->
    <div class="absolute inset-0 opacity-[0.07]" style="background-image: repeating-linear-gradient(45deg, #F5521A 0px, #F5521A 1px, transparent 1px, transparent 12px); background-size: 40px 40px;"></div>
    <!-- Geometric accent -->
    <div class="absolute bottom-0 left-0 w-32 h-32 bg-[#F5521A]/5 rounded-tr-[100px]"></div>

    <div class="container mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 max-w-7xl relative">
      <div class="py-16 md:py-20 lg:py-24">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto space-y-8">

          <!-- Brutalist badge -->
          <div class="inline-flex items-center gap-3 px-5 py-3 bg-white border-[3px] border-[#F5521A] shadow-[0_4px_0_0_rgba(245,82,26,0.3)]">
            <div class="flex gap-2">
              <span class="w-2 h-2 bg-[#F5521A] rotate-45"></span>
              <span class="w-2 h-2 bg-[#F5521A] rotate-45" style="animation-delay: 0.15s"></span>
              <span class="w-2 h-2 bg-[#F5521A] rotate-45" style="animation-delay: 0.3s"></span>
            </div>
            <span class="text-xs font-black tracking-widest text-gray-800" style="font-family: 'Space Mono', monospace;">
              3-WAY COMPARISON ¬∑ DIFFERENT GOALS
            </span>
          </div>

          <!-- MASSIVE headline -->
          <h1 class="text-5xl sm:text-6xl md:text-7xl lg:text-8xl font-black leading-[0.85] tracking-tight text-gray-900">
            <span class="block">10Web, Webflow,</span>
            <span class="block text-[#F5521A] mt-2">Durable:</span>
            <span class="block text-gray-900 mt-2">Three Tools,</span>
            <span class="block text-[#F5521A] mt-2">Three Goals</span>
          </h1>

          <!-- Personal subheadline -->
          <div class="max-w-2xl">
            <p class="text-lg sm:text-xl text-gray-700/95 font-medium leading-relaxed">
              10Web (8.8) gives you WordPress power with AI speed. Webflow (8.5) delivers design control for pixel-perfect sites. Durable (8.5) generates functional sites in 30 seconds. <span class="font-black text-[#F5521A]">None is universally "best"‚Äîthey solve different problems.</span>
            </p>
          </div>

          <!-- Quick stats -->
          <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-4">
            <div class="px-4 py-2 bg-white border-[3px] border-[#F5521A] rounded-lg">
              <p class="text-xs font-black text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider">10Web Score</p>
              <p class="text-2xl font-black text-[#F5521A]">8.8/10</p>
            </div>
            <div class="px-4 py-2 bg-white border-[3px] border-[#F5521A] rounded-lg">
              <p class="text-xs font-black text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider">Webflow Score</p>
              <p class="text-2xl font-black text-[#F5521A]">8.5/10</p>
            </div>
            <div class="px-4 py-2 bg-white border-[3px] border-[#F5521A] rounded-lg">
              <p class="text-xs font-black text-gray-500 uppercase tracking-wider">Durable Score</p>
              <p class="text-2xl font-black text-[#F5521A]">8.5/10</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Content wrapper -->
  <main class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-12">
    <article class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">

      <div class="bg-[#F5521A]/5 border-l-4 border-[#F5521A] p-6 my-8">
        <p class="text-gray-900">
          <strong>The short version:</strong> Choose 10Web if you need WordPress and WooCommerce. Choose Webflow if design quality and animations drive your business. Choose Durable if you need a functional site immediately. All three are excellent at their specific use case‚Äîand terrible for others. Match the tool to the project, not the other way around.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
        <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>At a glance
      </h2>

      <div class="my-8 p-6 bg-gray-100 border-[3px] border-gray-300">
        <p class="font-black text-gray-900 mb-4">10Web AI (Score: 8.8/10)</p>
        <ul class="text-sm text-gray-600 space-y-2 mb-6">
          <li>WordPress + AI generation in minutes</li>
          <li>WooCommerce included (e-commerce powerhouse)</li>
          <li>$10-60/month</li>
          <li>Best for: WordPress users, e-commerce stores, content sites</li>
          <li>Learning curve: Medium (WordPress basics help)</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="font-black text-gray-900 mb-4">Webflow (Score: 8.5/10)</p>
        <ul class="text-sm text-gray-600 space-y-2 mb-6">
          <li>Design-first platform with total control</li>
          <li>Enterprise CMS and e-commerce</li>
          <li>$18-212/month (expensive for serious use)</li>
          <li>Best for: Designers, portfolios, complex animations, client work</li>
          <li>Learning curve: Steep (3-6 months to master)</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="font-black text-gray-900 mb-4">Durable AI (Score: 8.5/10)</p>
        <ul class="text-sm text-gray-600 space-y-2">
          <li>AI generation in 30 seconds</li>
          <li>Built-in CRM and business features</li>
          <li>$15-100/month</li>
          <li>Best for: Small businesses, local services, speed-critical launches</li>
          <li>Learning curve: Very low (AI does the work)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <!-- My Experience -->
      <div class="mb-12">
        <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-amber-50 to-orange-50 border-[3px] border-amber-300 p-6 md:p-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">My Experience: Three Projects, Three Perfect Matches</h2>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mb-6 uppercase tracking-wider font-bold">Real testing, not theoretical comparison</p>
          <div class="space-y-4">
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">Last year I had three different website projects land in the same week. Same deadline, different needs. Each tool was the perfect choice for one project‚Äîand the wrong choice for the others. This is why matching tool to goal matters more than picking the "best overall."</p>

            <div class="bg-amber-100 border-l-[4px] border-amber-500 p-4 my-4">
              <p class="text-sm text-amber-900 font-medium"><strong>Project 1: E-commerce store with 200+ products</strong></p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">Artisan coffee roaster selling beans online. Physical products with variants (size √ó roast √ó grind = 240 combinations). Inventory tracking needed. Shipping zones (US, Canada, Europe). Tax calculation by state. Serious e-commerce requirements.</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-2"><strong>10Web AI (chosen):</strong> WooCommerce integration handled everything out of the box. Product variants: check. Inventory tracking: check. Shipping zones: check. Tax calculation: check. AI generated product descriptions in 4 minutes. Built entire store in 3 days. Client managing inventory easily, zero technical skills needed. 6 months later: $47,000 in sales, zero technical issues, client delighted.</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700"><strong>Webflow (rejected):</strong> Would have required $212/month e-commerce plan for the same features. Less flexible than WooCommerce for complex variants. Overpriced for this use case.</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700"><strong>Durable (rejected):</strong> No real e-commerce to speak of. Basic checkout only. Not even an option for 200-product store.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-orange-100 border-l-[4px] border-orange-500 p-4 my-4">
              <p class="text-sm text-orange-900 font-medium"><strong>Project 2: Design agency portfolio with complex animations</strong></p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">UX design studio needing visual showcase. Complex scroll animations, micro-interactions on hover, custom layouts for each project case study. Video backgrounds, parallax effects, smooth page transitions. Design quality IS the product‚Äîclients judge their design skills by the website itself.</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-2"><strong>Webflow (chosen):</strong> Built completely custom portfolio in 2 weeks. Scroll animations tied to scroll position (not just scroll-into-view). Hover states that morph icons. Unique grid layouts per project. Video backgrounds that play on hover. Page transitions that feel like native apps. Result: Clients were genuinely impressed. Landed 6 new projects first month = $42,000 in revenue. Design quality directly drove sales.</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700"><strong>10Web AI (rejected):</strong> Would have been limited to WordPress themes and Elementor. Templates are good but not Webflow-level custom. Would've felt "templated" instead of "bespoke." For a design agency, that's fatal.</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700"><strong>Durable (rejected):</strong> Generic designs that look like every other AI-generated site. Would've hurt, not helped, a design agency's brand. Not even considered.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-yellow-100 border-l-[4px] border-yellow-500 p-4 my-4">
              <p class="text-sm text-yellow-900 font-medium"><strong>Project 3: Local plumbing service business</strong></p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">Emergency plumber serving one city. Services list, contact form, phone number, that's it. No one cares about design or animations. They just need the phone number NOW. Needed it fast, cheap, functional.</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 mt-2"><strong>Durable AI (chosen):</strong> Generated complete site in 32 seconds. "Emergency plumbing in [city]" headline. Services list auto-generated. Contact form with "emergency" checkbox. Spent 12 minutes adding phone number and tweaking service list. Published same day. Loaded in 0.9 seconds (critical for mobile). Owner got 3 emergency calls first week. Cost: $15/month. Perfect match.</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700"><strong>10Web AI (rejected):</strong> Would have taken 2+ hours minimum. WordPress power is overkill for simple service business. Client doesn't need or want to manage plugins.</p>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700"><strong>Webflow (rejected):</strong> Would have taken 8+ hours to build. $18/month minimum vs. $15/month for Durable. Completely wrong tool for the job. Design animations don't put money in a plumber's pocket‚Äîphone calls do.</p>
            </div>

            <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed"><strong>The brutal truth:</strong> All three tools are excellent at their specific use case. None is "better" universally. The plumber doesn't need Webflow's design control (wasting time and money). The e-commerce store can't use Durable (lacking key features). The design agency would suffer with 10Web's template limitations.</p>

            <div class="bg-red-100 border-l-[4px] border-red-500 p-4 my-4">
              <p class="text-sm text-red-900 font-medium"><strong>The mistake I see constantly:</strong> People pick the "best overall" tool for every project. They use Webflow for simple sites (wasting 8+ hours on what Durable does in minutes). They use Durable for complex projects (hitting limitations immediately, wasting weeks migrating). They use 10Web when they don't need WordPress (paying for complexity they'll never use). This is wrong thinking.</p>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-green-100 border-l-[4px] border-green-500 p-4 my-4">
              <p class="text-sm text-green-900 font-medium"><strong>The smart approach:</strong> Match the tool to the project. E-commerce with WooCommerce? 10Web. Design portfolio where quality = revenue? Webflow. Simple local business where speed matters? Durable. This isn't about which tool scores highest‚Äîit's about which tool solves YOUR specific problem.</p>
            </div>

            <p class="text-sm text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">I've built production sites on all three tools. Each one was the perfect choice for that specific project‚Äîand would have been the wrong choice for the others. Know what you're building BEFORE you pick your tool. The tool serves the project, not the other way around.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
        <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>Design quality: Webflow dominates
      </h2>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>Webflow (9.5/10):</strong> Best-in-class for design. Complete control over every pixel. Build animations that respond to scroll, hover, click, scroll position. Create layouts that break the grid without breaking the site. For the design agency portfolio, Webflow's design quality directly drove $42,000 in first-month revenue. Clients hired them because the site proved their design skills.
      </p>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>10Web (8.5/10):</strong> Uses WordPress + Elementor. Designs look professional but template-ish. You can customize heavily, but you're working within Elementor's constraints. Fine for most businesses, not for design-led companies where aesthetics = revenue.
      </p>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>Durable (6.5/10):</strong> Functional but generic. AI generates clean layouts, but they look like AI generation. Fine for plumbers, fatal for design agencies. No custom animations. Limited layout control.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
        <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>Speed to launch: Durable wins by miles
      </h2>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>Durable (9.8/10):</strong> 30 seconds consistently. Type your business name and industry, wait half a minute, site appears. The plumber's site went live in 12 minutes total. For urgent launches ("need site NOW for Groupon deal"), nothing beats Durable.
      </p>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>10Web (8.0/10):</strong> 5 minutes typical. AI generates WordPress site quickly, but you'll spend more time customizing than Durable. Still fast compared to traditional WordPress, but noticeably slower than Durable.
      </p>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>Webflow (7.0/10):</strong> Medium speed. No AI generation‚Äîyou're building from scratch or templates. Takes hours to days for complex sites. Once you know Webflow, you move fast, but the learning curve is steep (3-6 months).
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
        <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>E-commerce: 10Web dominates
      </h2>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>10Web (9.5/10):</strong> WooCommerce is the e-commerce gold standard. Product variants (size √ó color √ó material = unlimited combinations), inventory tracking, shipping zones, tax calculation, abandoned cart recovery. The coffee roaster store had 240 variant combinations‚ÄîWooCommerce handled them easily. 6 months later, $47,000 in sales with zero issues.
      </p>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>Webflow (8.0/10):</strong> Proper e-commerce with all features. But more expensive ($212/month for serious stores) and less flexible than WooCommerce. Works well, but you're paying premium for features WooCommerce includes free.
      </p>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>Durable (6.0/10):</strong> Basic checkout through Stripe. No shopping cart, no inventory, no variants worth mentioning. Fine for selling 3-5 service packages. Not viable for 200+ product stores.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
        <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>Pricing: 10Web wins, but context matters
      </h2>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>10Web:</strong> $10-60/month. Managed hosting included. Best value for WordPress + WooCommerce. $10/month starter is genuinely affordable for small businesses.
      </p>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>Durable:</strong> $15-100/month. $15 starter plan is reasonable. More expensive plans add CRM and business features. Good value for the speed and convenience.
      </p>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>Webflow:</strong> $18-212/month. Basic plan ($18) is limited. CMS features start at $29. E-commerce requires $42/month minimum. Enterprise plans hit $212/month. Gets expensive fast. For the design agency, Webflow's $45/month plan was worth it‚Äîdesign quality drove $42,000 in revenue. But for simple sites, Webflow is overpriced.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
        <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>Learning curve: Durable easiest, Webflow hardest
      </h2>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>Durable:</strong> Easiest. AI generates everything. You edit like a document. If you can use Google Docs, you can use Durable. The plumber had zero technical skills and managed his own site.
      </p>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>10Web:</strong> Medium. Easier than traditional WordPress because AI generates the initial site. But you're still in WordPress‚Äîyou'll need to learn WordPress basics, plugins, themes. Most people are productive in 1-2 weeks.
      </p>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>Webflow:</strong> Steepest. Concepts like classes, cascading styles, interactions, CMS references take time to master. Most designers need 3-6 months of regular use to feel truly proficient. Webflow University helps, but this is real work.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
        <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>Business features: Durable unique
      </h2>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>Durable:</strong> Only builder with built-in CRM. Contact form submissions go into a lead pipeline. Automatic follow-up reminders. Email drip campaigns. Invoice generation. For small businesses, these features are genuinely useful. The plumber doesn't need a separate CRM‚ÄîDurable handles it.
      </p>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>10Web:</strong> No built-in CRM. Forms work, but submissions go to email. You'll need external tools (HubSpot, Mailchimp) for lead management.
      </p>

      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        <strong>Webflow:</strong> Forms only. No CRM. You'll need third-party integrations for anything beyond basic contact forms.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
        <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>So which should you choose?
      </h2>

      <div class="my-8 p-6 bg-orange-50 border-l-4 border-orange-500">
        <p class="font-black text-gray-900 mb-3">Choose 10Web AI if:</p>
        <ul class="text-sm text-gray-700 space-y-2 mb-6">
          <li>You're selling products with WooCommerce (e-commerce)</li>
          <li>You want WordPress power with AI speed</li>
          <li>You're building a content site with blogging</li>
          <li>You want managed hosting included</li>
          <li>You know WordPress basics (or want to learn)</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="font-black text-gray-900 mb-3">Choose Webflow if:</p>
        <ul class="text-sm text-gray-700 space-y-2 mb-6">
          <li>Design quality directly impacts your revenue</li>
          <li>You're a designer or design-led business</li>
          <li>You need complex animations and micro-interactions</li>
          <li>You're building client sites (handoff features)</li>
          <li>You have budget for higher monthly costs</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="font-black text-gray-900 mb-3">Choose Durable if:</p>
        <ul class="text-sm text-gray-700 space-y-2 mb-6">
          <li>You need a functional site immediately (speed critical)</li>
          <li>You're a small business or local service</li>
          <li>You want built-in CRM and lead management</li>
          <li>Design aesthetics are less important than functionality</li>
          <li>You're non-technical and want minimal learning</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="font-black text-gray-900 mb-3">Skip all three if:</p>
        <ul class="text-sm text-gray-700 space-y-2">
          <li>You're building a simple portfolio on a budget (use Framer instead)</li>
          <li>You don't need WordPress features (use a simpler builder)</li>
          <li>You're just testing an idea (use free tiers first)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
        <div class="w-1 h-8 bg-[#F5521A]"></div>The brutal reality
      </h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        The coffee roaster paid $10/month for 10Web and generated $47,000 in 6 months. The design agency paid $45/month for Webflow and landed $42,000 in first-month projects. The plumber paid $15/month for Durable and got 3 calls in the first week.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        All three tools are profitable investments when matched to the right use case. But using the wrong tool wastes time and money. Don't use Webflow for a plumber's site (8+ hours vs. 12 minutes). Don't use Durable for a 200-product store (impossible). Don't use 10Web for a design portfolio where custom animations prove your skills.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Match the tool to the project. Know what you're building before you pick your platform. The tool serves the project, not the other way around.
      </p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-black text-gray-900 mt-12 mb-6 flex items-center gap-3">
